Over 70 percent of South African workers do not belong to a labour union. Some labour experts are putting the blame on unions for this. South African Federation of Trade Unions Secretary-General, Zwelinzima Vavi discussed this with eNCA's Gareth Edwards. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - South African Federation of Trade Unions Secretary General, Zwelinzima Vavi, is blaming capitalism and the intimidation of workers by employers for the low number of employees joining unions. Over 70 percent of South African workers are not unionised. WATCH:Â Labour Minister speaks on prioritising workers' rights "The blame must be put both on the doorsteps of the trade unions themselves but also on the brutality of the system of capitalism. "The bosses who intimidate workers and make sure that they are discouraged from forming part of the unions themselves," he said.